Start with a sketch. Rightward numbers (toward \(+\infty\)) will be more than our boundary \(z\), so we shade a rightward region with area 0.81.


You should first find the left area. \[\begin{aligned} P(Z<z) &= 1-P(Z>z) \\ &= 1-0.81 \\ &= 0.19 \end{aligned}\]

plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2

You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.19.

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-0.9 0.1841
-0.89 0.1867
-0.88 0.1894
-0.87 0.1922
-0.86 0.1949
-0.85 0.1977

It turns out the exact answer is \(z=-0.8778963\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

=Norm.Inv(0.19,0,1)

Using R:

rightarea = 0.81
leftarea = 1-rightarea
qnorm( leftarea )

But, the \(z\)-table is accurate enough, so I will accept either -0.88 or -0.87 (anything within 0.01 of -0.8778963).

You might find it helpful to visualize with a spinner.
